<taxonomicName authority="Dendy, 1913" authorityName="Dendy" authorityYear="1913" box="[151,510,732,757]" class="Calcarea" family="Leucettidae" genus="Pericharax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clathrinida" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="peziza">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,510,732,757]" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,357,732,757]" italics="true" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Pericharax peziza</emphasis>
Dendy, 1913
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="149.[151,1437,732,1009]" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">
Dendy (1913: 15) described this from 
<collectingRegion box="[593,793,768,793]" country="Mauritius" name="Cargados Carajos Shoals" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Cargados Carajos</collectingRegion>
as a species similar in spiculation to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van Soest &amp; De Voogd" authorityYear="2015" box="[1227,1365,768,793]" class="Calcarea" family="Leucettidae" genus="Pericharax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clathrinida" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="orientalis">
<emphasis box="[1227,1365,768,793]" italics="true" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">P. orientalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as 
<taxonomicName class="Calcarea" family="Leucettidae" genus="Pericharax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clathrinida" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="heteroraphis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">P. heteroraphis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), but with a cup-shaped form, size 
<quantity box="[695,772,805,829]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.7" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" unit="cm" value="3.7">3.7 cm</quantity>
diameter and a height of the cup of 
<quantity box="[1185,1266,805,829]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" unit="cm" value="2.9">2.9 cm</quantity>
. The cup walls are 
<quantity box="[195,273,841,865]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" unit="cm" value="0.7">0.7 cm</quantity>
in thickness and are smooth, unfurrowed. 
<bibRefCitation box="[769,931,840,865]" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" refId="ref64746" refString="Burton, M. (1963) Revision of the classification of the calcareous sponges. British Museum (Natural History), London, 693 pp." type="book">Burton (1963)</bibRefCitation>
synonymized the two, but Van Soest &amp; De Voogd (2015) considered it a separate species, following Dendy’s decision. The inside of the cup has numerous oscular openings. The giant triactines have actines of 1400 
<date box="[822,872,913,937]" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" value="1970-10">x 70</date>
µm, small choanosomal triactines have actines of 180 
<date box="[200,235,948,973]" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">x 5</date>
µm, cortical triactines are 100 x 5.5 µm, tetractines of the surfaces of the inner wall and canals up to 290 
<date pageId="149" pageNumber="150" value="2012-10">x 12</date>
µm, apical actines slightly crooked, up to 75 µm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
